# 二、Band 8 改写版（建议精读）

The bar chart compares the number of US households, measured in millions, across five annual income categories in 2007, 2011 and 2015.

Overall, households earning $100,000 or more experienced the most significant growth over the period, particularly in 2015. By contrast, the middle-income categories remained comparatively stable. In addition, households earning below $50,000 consistently represented a substantial proportion of the total throughout the three years.

In 2007, households with annual incomes of at least $100,000 constituted the largest category, at approximately 29 million. This was closely followed by those earning between $25,000 and $49,999, with around 27 million households. Meanwhile, roughly 25 million households earned less than $25,000 per year. The two middle-income groups were noticeably smaller, with about 21 million households in the $50,000–$74,999 bracket and only around 14 million earning between $75,000 and $99,999.

A similar pattern was observed in 2011, although the number of households earning below $25,000 rose to nearly 29 million, making it the largest category that year. By 2015, however, high-income households had increased dramatically to approximately 33 million, surpassing all other income groups. In contrast, the middle-income categories showed little change overall, while the number of households earning between $75,000 and $99,999 rose only marginally from around 14 million to 15 million.

